	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">These times I have been thinking about the better known alternative to Windows, that is especially popular among harcore informaticians.<br />Does anyone here have it ? Has anyone had a (good or bad) experience (trying) switching from Windows to Linux ? Is a Linux platform more or less suitable for homebrew developpement and emulation or does it make no difference ? Does it exists DOS emulators that allows one to run DOS programms under Linux (or even better, Windows emulator) ?</div>
<br />
<br />For about 6 straight years, I exclusively used Linux.  I ditched Windows cold turkey.  About 10 months ago, I got a new laptop that has Windows on it.  So now I know what it is like to go from Windows to Linux... and then many years later, from Linux to Windows.  I am writing this from one of my Linux computers.  I use Linux 90% of the time.  I use Windows to play games that do not have official Linux ports.
<br />
<br />Regardless of what the zealots say, Linux is not superior to Windows.  Similarly, Windows is not superior to Linux.  Both are crap... but then again, what other choice is there?  A Mac?  It is probably just as crappy as Linux and Windows.
<br />
<br />If you need to run several Windows applications, do not try to switch to Linux because emulation of Windows is a huge pain in the ass.  However, many applications that people think that they need when switching over to Linux, are not needed because there usually are suitable alternative applications.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


